With this in mind, they sought to marry agriculture and mentoring young people in Kitale. They started agribusiness on five acres to sustain the home with 40 girls and helping them return to school. Farmers are advised exactly what they need to do, including time frame and budget. This is followed by training on Good Agricultural Practices (GAP) at the Fresh Produce Exporters Association of Kenya (FPEAK). This covers use of fertilisers and pesticides, among other things. This is followed by a final certification audit for domestic or international scope. 